Observation Details: Continuing. Seen in the channel on the right side of the trail, specifically, to the east of the east pond, about 3/4 of the way from the trailhead to the north bend of the pond. We saw the bird near a large flock of Mallards, but we were able to identify the Brant by the black head, slightly larger size than Mallard, brown body, and larger white rump. We observed the bird swimming back and forth with the Mallards in the channel for about 10 minutes before deciding to move on.
Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

Checklist Comments: An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. Scattered clouds Temperature: 44 - 53°F Wind: Light breeze Wind Direction: N Cloud Cover: 41 - 47% Humidity: 57 - 71% Weather generated by RainCrow

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Observation Details: Woohoo! After scanning the second pond south of the Unit 1 parking for about 10 minutes, we spotted a Stilt Sandpiper in the northeast corner, at about (33.0799871, -115.7104158). It gave us excellent prolonged looks as it foraged, mixing more with the dowitchers and ibises than with the peeps. Much larger than Western Sandpipers; slightly taller than dowitchers, but slimmer and smaller overall. Bill long and ever so slightly decurved, but shorter than dowitcher bills. Long, yellow legs. Overall, very gray with no brownish tones. Whenever the Stilt Sandpiper bent over to forage, we noted the primaries and tertials were very ruffled, giving it an almost hedgehog-like appearance, making it easy to pick out from among the dowitchers. Photos to be uploaded.

Observation Details: Continuing among Western Sandpipers in the southwest corner of Pond 23. First seen around 9:30 am, on the far, low patch of mud at (32.5919947, -117.1140087). Then, it flew to “stint island”, where it first foraged on the low side of the island at (32.5913097, -117.1132889), and then continued foraging behind the mounds on the right side of the island, out of sight from the viewing platform. The stint stood out readily from the Western Sandpipers next to it. The key field marks we all noted, relative to WESA: a scalier, browner back, a much shorter, slightly decurved bill, and smaller size overall. The legs were black, seen in good lighting from multiple angles. In the scope and binoculars, we could not clearly discern the distinctive facial pattern with the split supercilium, which troubled us, until we took photos that clearly showed the same facial pattern as the Little Stint. Photos attached.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

We parked in the narrow, grassy shoulder of Kincaid Rd, not next to any driveways, where there are No Trespassing signs posted. A rancher from one of the nearby properties came out and told us he didn’t mind us doing what we were doing, but that one of the other property owners might not take so kindly to people birding on the road because they’ve had experiences with “sketchy people” coming up the road to steal from their mailboxes. So I would recommend taking caution while birding this area and making sure not to walk anywhere off the road onto private property (all our observations were from standing on the road).

We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. Observation Details: Tristan and I saw an empid low in the big euc, and I passed it off as a Pac-slope until I saw Tristan’s photos - they showed a rather grayish flycatcher with a short, narrow bill, long primary projections, and a short tail. It turned out Carter G. and Steve R. were also looking at this bird at the same time, and looking at Tristan’s photos we all thought it looked very likely to be a Hammond’s. Later, Steve R. got better looks at the flycatcher and was able to confirm it was a Hammond’s, but when everybody else came around the bird flew high up into the euc and was seen only a few more times. Tristan has good photos from when it was low in the euc.

Continuing wintering bird. First spotted in the undergrowth around (37.4061985, -121.9214778), right opposite the end of Sycamore Dr, but it quickly dove back into the bushes and could not be refound. Then, while walking along the creek about 45 minutes later, we spotted it again on some logs right next to the trail at (37.4058978, -121.9223341). It then flitted across the trail to a weeping willow, where we heard and recorded it call a high, sharp “pik!” about 20 times. When it was perched next to the trail, our impression was of a small empid with mostly grayish-green tones and a tiny, needle-like black bill with no orange on the lower mandible. When it was perched in the willow, Tristan snapped some photos showing the long primary projections and relatively short tail, clinching the ID. -Sergey

Two individuals seen at the same time, just west of the bridge along Isabel Creek. We heard high, sharp “peek” calls coming from the creek bed, and played Hammond’s Flycatcher calls from Merlin, which matched up exactly with what we were hearing. Soon after we initiated playback, one empid popped up high in a valley oak at a distance of around 50-60 ft, providing great binocular views. We could tell that it was a rather dull gray flycatcher, much duller than the Pac-slope we had just observed, with a thin, short, dark bill, long primary projections, and short tail. This bird called in response to our playback, but calls continued coming from a different region of the creek bed, and soon another empid appeared in a different valley oak, about 100 ft from the oak where the first flycatcher remained perched. It matched the same exact description as the first empid, and the calls were identical to the first empid’s. Tristan has good photos of both birds from when they were perched apart from each other, although eventually they ended up in the same oak. Interestingly, the two empids never interacted directly while we watched - rather, they were chased first by a Yellow-rumped Warbler, then an Oak Titmouse.

Location: Vina Vieja, Gwinn and Sunnyslope Parks
Observation Details: Flew into a tree in the northwest corner of Vina Vieja Park, sat there for a minute, and then dipped back into the vegetation along Eaton Wash, where we couldn’t refind it, despite much effort. Our impression was of a rather small empid, with bright yellow belly contrasting with gray breast, eyering shape unlike that of Pac-slope, and rather short bill. The bill looked too short for Gray, and the tail was not being wagged downwards. We did not get a good read on the primary projection or tail length in the field. Tristan got one photo, but it is unfortunately too blurry to interpret the primary projection or tail length, and the bird’s head is turned away, with the bill not visible. We feel it is safest to leave this bird as Hammond’s/Dusky Flycatcher, but reviewer feedback on the photo is welcome.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. We chased it briefly and took photos before departing, for a total observation time of approximately 5 minutes.

An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

Location: Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)
Observation Details: Both birds seen in flight by the radar tower. The first one passed over going south, then wheeled around to face us and passed over to the north, flew along the channel parallel the east side of the east pond and disappeared out of sight. The second one flew over us and along the channel seconds later, so there were two birds - I don’t see how the first one could have covered the several hundred yards of distance back around us in just a few seconds. On both birds, we noted a warm brown back and white underparts, interrupted by a dark, crisp breastband that came to a point down the breast. We also noticed, on both birds, a partial white collar coming up around the back of the neck. Not juvenile Tree Swallows: both swallows were quite small, the back color was too warm, and the line dividing light and dark on the face was not sharply demarcated like on a Tree Swallow. Not juvenile VG: they had no white markings over or around the eye, and the breast bands were clearly visible. Not NRWS: again, the breast bands were crisp and dark, the white collars stood out, and there was a noticeable division between brown and white on the face, not completely washed out like on NRWS. Unfortunately, we couldn’t get photos in flight, but our looks at both birds were prolonged enough to be confident they were Bank Swallows.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Checklist Comments: An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. Scattered clouds Temperature: 44 - 53°F Wind: Light breeze Wind Direction: N Cloud Cover: 41 - 47% Humidity: 57 - 71% Weather generated by RainCrow

Observation Details: Known roosting site at the underpass. Swallows were circling high when we arrived and gradually came lower and lower until they began entering their roost in groups of 5-30 individuals at 5:43 pm. Estimated at least 150 on the near side of the bridge, and 150 on the far side, in groups of 25. All swallows with orange throat, forehead, and rump, blue head without white spot as in Cliff, creamy white underparts, and squared-off tail.

We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

Checklist Comments: An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. Checklist Comments: Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. Observation Details: Rattle call heard from the field on the east side of Vendel Rd, just south of the Unit 1 parking, as soon as we parked around 3:50 pm, but not heard again. Clearly coming from a bird moving in flight, at least several hundred feet out into the field, but the bird itself was never seen. We heard maybe 4 or 5 phrases before the bird went silent (presumably landed). The calls sounded drier than the Lapland Longspur recordings in the Merlin app, but perhaps still ok for that species. We didn’t hear any “tew” calls interspersed between the rattle calls. Wished we could have looked for the longspur, but we decided to look for Stilt Sandpiper in the ponds to the west of the road instead, and it paid off!

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Huge numbers of ducks today along the south side of the west pond of the WPCP. Mostly shovelers in the southeast corner, but the southwest corner had a mixed species flock that we estimated had about 6000 ducks in total, when they were all flushed up by three fighter jets taking off from Moffett Field. We estimated the proportions as about 1/2 American Wigeon, 1/3 Northern Pintail, and 1/10 Green-winged Teal, with the rest being made up of diving ducks.

An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. It's back and wings had messy but contrasting black and white stripes. It's head showed a white median crown stripe with black lateral crown stripes. It had a white face with messy gray lores and black eyeline. Its white chin led to a slightly darker belly with lots of black stripes. It's toes were long with a hint of yellow. The relatively low contrast on the belly and white throat and no evidence of buffy or yellow shades on the body leads me to believe this bird is an adult female, though I would like some help on that identification.   The bird continued to crawl and hop around the same Sycamore for about 10 minutes. I didn't hear it call or follow it for long.  Pictures attached.

Spotted creeping around a tree in the middle of the river (37.342123,-121.902134). Most likely continuing as I spotted it about 200 meters from where I had previously seen another female Black-and-white Warbler. Did not call during the 5 minutes that I observed the bird. Pictures attached.
Checklist Comments: Not as many migrants as I had hoped, but wintering vagrants are good too!

Observation Details: Looked for a few minutes where I saw it last.

Yet another long and sharp-billed black and white warbler. Spotted by my non-birder girlfriend while she was sitting on the swings waiting for me to be done birding. Seen hopping and crawling in a barren tree at (37.35969128831732, -121.98984420077416) at 12:50 PM. Its back and wings had messy but contrasting black and white stripes. Its head showed a white median crown stripe with black lateral crown stripes. It had a white face with messy gray lores and a fine, but very contrasting black eyeline. Its white chin led to a slightly darker belly with lots of black stripes. Its toes were long and very yellow. The low contrast striping on the breast and belly, the slightly brownish tinge on the primary coverts, and slightly pointed rectrices make me believe this is a immature female.  The bird quickly left the tree adjacent to the playground and flew south into some conifers at the edge of the park (37.359098293938786, -121.98962579887912) where I lost it in the dense branches.  My guess is that this is a separate individual to the one I saw just five days ago at Guadalupe River Park. The dark edge of the neck-side of the auricular on the left side of the birds face is less contrasting on this individual and darker and clearer on the one from Guadalupe River Park. Once again I am open to feedback on this sighting.    EDIT: In my conversation with Marty Freeland, he gave evidence to this bird being a juvenile male. There are traces of black feathering on the chin and throat. This information is enough to conclude that this individual is a separate one from the one I saw five days ago. Incredible! There are two Black-and-white Warblers in Santa Clara now.    EDIT: In my more recent conversation with Marty Freeland, he told me about how he went out to study the warbler in-person. After more careful observation of the bird through his eyes, he determined that the dark traces on the bird's throat and chin were merely artifacts of lighting. He concluded that the bird is in fact a female.

I was walking back to my car after the excitement of seeing two American Bitterns. In Chris Hotts Park right next to where I parked, a very close White-breasted Nuthatch caught my attention and I was back to birding. I looked up and a warbler with a contrasting head caught my attention. I looked closer at where the wire entered the nearest house (37.24546233569403, -121.8758197893505) and I saw a warbler with a sharp pointed bill, a gray face with a dark eyeline, an olive neck and back, gray wings, a pale belly, and an extensively white vent and undertail coverts. The bird perched on the wires, pecking at wall of the house then flew a few meters up into the nearest trees where I lost sight of it. I didn't follow it further as I had to leave to get back to the office for work. Pictures attached.

Checklist Comments: An awesome morning at the lower saddle! This was my first time seeing a true morning flight. We arrived after sunrise, but before sun had illuminated the saddle. Until this happened, at about 7:10 am, activity was very slow, with just a few YRWA moving by. However, as soon as sunlight hit the saddle, there was a burst of activity, and small flocks of YRWA, with occasional TOWA mixed in, began flying up the canyon from SCZ, and crossing the road into SCL. It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. We parked in the narrow, grassy shoulder of Kincaid Rd, not next to any driveways, where there are No Trespassing signs posted. A rancher from one of the nearby properties came out and told us he didn’t mind us doing what we were doing, but that one of the other property owners might not take so kindly to people birding on the road because they’ve had experiences with “sketchy people” coming up the road to steal from their mailboxes. So I would recommend taking caution while birding this area and making sure not to walk anywhere off the road onto private property (all our observations were from standing on the road).

Observation Details: Didn't get a good look and didn't get any photos. Heard the tink call a couple of times over the dozens of Yellow-rumped Warblers. I heard it a couple of times when I first noticed the bird and once more about 30 minutes later when I was waiting for the bird to return to get better looks. Sounded like it could have been either Townsend's or Hermit. From my poor looks, I saw a thick but faint black line going through the eye on a mostly bright yellow face. I also noticed a lot more white on the breast and neck than on most Townsend's. In conclusion, this is possibly a Hermit or Hermit x Townsend's.

It was the first time we've seen warblers flocking in flight like this. Migrant numbers were highest before 8 am, but diversity peaked after 8 am, with more OCWA, TOWA, BTYW, and HEWA relative to YRWA. Despite a very poor prognosis from Birdcast the morning of (only 10,000 birds crossing SCL the previous night), we ended up having a great morning! Conditions were partly cloudy, and rather warm (felt like 50-55 F), with gusts of wind 10-15 mph from variable directions, but mainly from the north. This wind did not preclude warblers from continuing their flight north, although it did complicate the task. Looks great as always, fanning tail frequently.

Continuing, amazing find yesterday by Meg Barron and Ellyn Corey. Refound today by Richard Jeffers at around 4 pm in the oak at (37.3926426, -121.9534172), and the group of 20 or so birders assembled by the eucalyptus where the redstart had previously been seen all sprinted over. We got great looks as it foraged, twisting and turning and hanging upside down from the big branches of the oak - it seemed to favor these branches over thinner branches and leaves. Then, several minutes later, it disappeared and nobody could refind it for the next two hours, despite much effort. Stunning bird, with red breast, black back and head, and white wing patch and outer tail feathers. Tristan might have some identifiable photos, but I just got its tail poking out from behind a branch.

Continuing. Seen at around 9:20am at (37.3926977, -121.9534326).  We were looking at a Western Bluebird perched on the lightpost when we heard a clear, loud and sharp call coming from the tree beside us. We saw the Painted Redstart hopping between branches in the tree. In flight, the bird appeared mostly black with red flashes. Once it landed, we clearly saw the large white wingbars, black body, and red belly. The bird remained moving around in the tree for about a minute or two before we lost it. We continued searching but weren't able to refind it. Photos attached.
Stood under thr oak tree where the Redstart has been seen before at (37.392707,-121.953500) for about 30 minutes. Did not hear or see it the entire time.

Continuing in the tree just southwest of the Administration Building (37.393363 -121.955210). Called a couple of times in the 5 minutes I observed it, but was mostly silent. Flashed it's tail many times and moved around constantly like a Ruby-crowned Kinglet. Photo attached.
Very likely Hermit, seen only in flight, strangely going south.

We parked in the narrow, grassy shoulder of Kincaid Rd, not next to any driveways, where there are No Trespassing signs posted. A rancher from one of the nearby properties came out and told us he didn’t mind us doing what we were doing, but that one of the other property owners might not take so kindly to people birding on the road because they’ve had experiences with “sketchy people” coming up the road to steal from their mailboxes. So I would recommend taking caution while birding this area and making sure not to walk anywhere off the road onto private property (all our observations were from standing on the road).
Surprisingly slow for warblers. Maybe still too early in the season?
